I found **three approaches** on how to address this problem:
* Iterate through the array `nums1`, maintaining separate indices for both arrays. And for every encounter element in the `nums2` that is less than a current element in `nums1` shift the elements of the `nums1` starting from the current and assign the element from the `nums2` to the current position. In worse case when shifting has to be done for every element in the `nums2` (*all element in the second arrays smaller than the first value first array*) it&#39;ll perform in a quadratic time. I.e. **O(n * m)** (*that is the approach that OP tried to implement*). And also this solution is probably the simplest one. 
* The second approach is to create an array of length identical to `nums1`. Iterate over the newly created array and populate it with the smallest values from the `nums1` and `nums2` for each step of the iteration. Then because `nums1` requires to be modified, all its contents should be replaced with elements from the new array. Time complexity of this approach is **O(n + m)** but memory consumption will be a bit greater.
* The third approach requires to allocate a new array of size `nums2.length` that will basically act like **queue** (array is used instead of collection in order to keep focus on the algorithm and make the solution more digestible for beginners). The idea of this algorithm to modify the `nums1` in place while iterating over it by choosing the smallest value for each iteration from `nums1`, `nums2`, and **queue**. The difference between this and previous approach is that array size will be smaller (because `nums1.length &gt;= nums2.length`) and there will be no need to copy the contents of the **queue** to the `nums1`. I.e. it requires less operation and has a better memory consumption. Therefore, this approach is the **most performance-wise**.

The **first approach** (shifting the elements in the *first array* when a smaller value in the *second array* was encountered)

    public static void merge(int[] nums1, int m, int[] nums2, int n) {
        if (nums2.length == 0) { // in this case there must be no trailing zeros in the NUMS1
            return;
        }
        // index for nums2
        int ind2 = 0;

        for (int ind1 = 0; ind1 &lt; nums1.length &amp;&amp; ind2 &lt; nums2.length; ind1++) {
            if (nums1[ind1] &lt;= nums2[ind2] &amp;&amp; nums1[ind1] != 0) {
                continue; // no need change anything
            }
            // shifting all non-zero elements on the right from &quot;prev&quot; by 1 to the right
            int prev = nums1[ind1];
            for (int i = ind1 + 1; i &lt; nums1.length &amp;&amp; prev != 0; i++) {
                int next = nums1[i];
                nums1[i] = prev;
                prev = next;
            }
            nums1[ind1] = nums2[ind2++]; // assigning element from NUMS2 to the current position in NUMS1 and moving index of the NUMS2
        }
    }

The **second approach** (to use an *intermediate array* of size `nums2.length`).

    public static void merge(int[] nums1, int m, int[] nums2, int n) {
        if (nums2.length == 0) { // in this case there must be no trailing zeros in the NUMS1
            return;
        }
        // indices for nums1 and nums2
        int ind1 = 0;
        int ind2 = 0;

        int[] res = new int[nums1.length]; // result

        for (int i = 0; i &lt; res.length; i++) {
            if (ind2 == n ||  // index of the NUMS2 was exceeded
                    (ind1 &lt; m &amp;&amp; nums1[ind1] &lt; nums2[ind2])) { // index of the NUMS1 wasn&#39;t exceeded &amp;&amp; value in the NUMS1 is less than value in the NUMS2
                res[i] = nums1[ind1++];
            }
            else {
                res[i] = nums2[ind2++];
            }
        }
        System.arraycopy(res, 0, nums1, 0, res.length);
    }

The **third approach** (to use **queue**).

    public static void merge(int[] nums1, int m, int[] nums2, int n) {
        if (nums2.length == 0) { // in this case there must be no trailing zeros in the NUMS1
            return;
        }
        // indices for nums1 and nums2
        int ind1 = 0;
        int ind2 = 0;

        int[] queue = new int[nums2.length]; // queue
        int put = 0; // queue indices
        int take = 0;

        for (;ind1 &lt; nums1.length; ind1++) {
            if (take &lt; queue.length &amp;&amp; queue[take] != 0 &amp;&amp; // index of the QUEUE wasn&#39;t exceeded &amp;&amp; value in the QUEUE is NOT zero
                    ((ind2 == n || nums2[ind2] &gt; queue[take]) // index of the NUMS2 was exceeded || value in the queue is less than value in the NUMS2
                            &amp;&amp; (ind1 &gt;= m || nums1[ind1] &gt; queue[take]))) { // value in the NUMS1 is zero (range M of non-zero values was exceeded) || value in the queue is less than value in the NUMS1
                
                if (ind1 &lt; m) { // value in the NUMS1 is NOT zero and therefor has to be stored in QUEUE
                    queue[put] = nums1[ind1]; // making a copy of the element &amp;&amp; moving put index of the QUEUE index to the right
                    put = ++put % queue.length;
                }
                // assigning value from the QUEUE &amp;&amp; moving take of the QUEUE index to the right
                nums1[ind1] = queue[take];
                take = ++take % queue.length;
            }
            else if (ind2 &lt; n &amp;&amp; // index of the NUMS2 was exceeded
                    (ind1 &gt;= m || nums1[ind1] &gt; nums2[ind2]) &amp;&amp; // value in the NUMS1 is a trailing zero || value in the NUMS2 is less than value in the NUMS1
                    (take == queue.length || // position in the QUEUE is illegal ||
                            queue[take] == 0 || queue[take] &gt; nums2[ind2])) { // value in the QUEUE is zero || value in NUMS2 is the smallest
                // making a copy of the element &amp;&amp; moving put index of the QUEUE index to the right
                queue[put] = nums1[ind1];
                put = ++put % queue.length;
                // assigning value from the NUMS2 to the element in NUMS1 &amp;&amp; moving NUMS2 index to the right
                nums1[ind1] = nums2[ind2++];
            }
        }
    }

**main()**

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] nums1 ={1,2,4,0,0,0};
        int[] nums2 = {2,5,6};
        merge(nums1, nums1.length - nums2.length, nums2, nums2.length);
        System.out.println(Arrays.toString(nums1));

        nums1 = new int[]{2,0};
        nums2 = new int[]{1};
        merge(nums1, nums1.length - nums2.length, nums2, nums2.length);
        System.out.println(Arrays.toString(nums1));
    }

**output** (for all versions)
```
[1, 2, 2, 4, 5, 6]
[1, 2]
```
**Note:**
* Condition `if (nums2.length == 0)` at the beginning of each implementation will terminate the method execution if the second array is empty.
* This statement `System.arraycopy(res, 0, nums1, 0, res.length);` in the implementation which utilizes an intermediate array is used to copy the contents of this array to `nums1`. The same result can be achieved by replacing [**`System.arraycopy()`**](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/System.html#arraycopy(java.lang.Object,int,java.lang.Object,int,int)) with the following `for` loop:
```
for (int i = 0; i &lt; nums1.length; i++) {
    nums[i] = res[i];
}
```

